        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2297199973" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15275517756735130491">Catching up on my comments from last time, I am awarding this five stars since I finally found an appreciation for the play years after I first read it. When I started reading plays in the late 1960&apos;s, O&apos;Neill was recognized as my country&apos;s greatest playwright. Unfortunately, I was occupied with more recent playwright&apos;s like Beckett, Pinter, Albee, Ionesco and Stoppard. In comparison, O&apos;Neill seemed stale and out of touch. I had last experienced the play in a 1987 televised adaptation featuring </span>
  <span id="freeText15275517756735130491" style="display:none">Catching up on my comments from last time, I am awarding this five stars since I finally found an appreciation for the play years after I first read it. When I started reading plays in the late 1960's, O'Neill was recognized as my country's greatest playwright. Unfortunately, I was occupied with more recent playwright's like Beckett, Pinter, Albee, Ionesco and Stoppard. In comparison, O'Neill seemed stale and out of touch. I had last experienced the play in a 1987 televised adaptation featuring Jack Lemmon and I did not care for that production at all. So I had pretty much given up on this play until this recent read when I had the pleasure of rereading the play and it clicked. I got it! I felt connected with the material and what the author was trying to communicate. I think that is one of the best joys one can have in reading. So my five stars are for that experience. As for the play itself-- it still seems a little dated, but the problems of opiate addiction, alcohol abuse, the dysfunctional family are as important today and O'Neill's depiction of the these characters as they progress into self-absorption and self-indulgence can give us cause to think.<br /><br /><br />Earlier comment.<br />This was a highlight of my reading week since I finally was able to appreciate this play after having dismissed it in my past. My tired brain isn't up to coherent comments so I will return to this review when I am refreshed.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15275517756735130491" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

