  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1781057824" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1781057824" />
    <a title="Brian Yahn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22849115-brian-yahn"><img alt="Brian Yahn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1464719293p2/22849115.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1781057824?book_show_action=true">Feb 12, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brian Yahn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brian Yahn" href="/user/show/22849115-brian-yahn">Brian Yahn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22849115-brian-yahn?shelf=plays">plays</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1781057824" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13602306574234680742"><b>Long Day&apos;s Journey into Night - this was my childhood, my life.</b><br/><br/>It hit home for me like no other family drama has. Mostly I was the younger brother (I am in real life), but at times I was the older brother and the father, even the mother occasionally, too.<br/><br/>The flaws these characters have are so extreme, but at the same time so relatable. They&apos;re mostly horrible creatures who hate each other. But they also love each other, deeply - in their own ways. And as a reader, you latch on to those ways, and</span>
  <span id="freeText13602306574234680742" style="display:none"><b>Long Day's Journey into Night - this was my childhood, my life.</b><br /><br />It hit home for me like no other family drama has. Mostly I was the younger brother (I am in real life), but at times I was the older brother and the father, even the mother occasionally, too.<br /><br />The flaws these characters have are so extreme, but at the same time so relatable. They're mostly horrible creatures who hate each other. But they also love each other, deeply - in their own ways. And as a reader, you latch on to those ways, and hope they triumph and come together as a family.<br /><br />Over and over in the play the characters say, "I loved you, in my own way."<br /><br />You hate your older brother when your younger, and yet you idolize him - want to be just like him. Your older brother wants you to hate him, because he wants you to be something different. He sees you walking down his path, and he wants you to walk down a better one, but he doesn't know how to get there, otherwise he'd be walking down that path himself. You're a reminder of his failures, and he hates <i>that</i>, not you.<br /><br />There's so many weird ways we express love for the people we care about the most - most of those aren't very healthy. This play really shines a light on a lot of those common ways.<br /><br />My family wasn't filled with alcoholics and drug addicts and traumatic deaths, of stars fallen from grace. We were pretty typical, in most ways. But we had all these complicated relationships, and I suspect almost all families do.<br /><br />Reading it from the extremes of these characters was healing in a lot of ways. The characters are so real, you can step inside them, and as you read the lines, it's like reliving your own family drama. And when you say the things they say - the things you never did but wished you did - you can lose yourself, and be relieved or healed. I became lost in the pages.<br /><br /><i>"I became drunk with the beauty and signing rhythm of it, and for a moment I lost myself--actually lost myself. I was set free! I dissolved in the sea, became white snails and flying spray, became beauty and rhythm, became moonlight and the ship and the high dim-starred sky."</i><br /><br />The story is set up a bit like a whodunit murder mystery. It pits the alcoholics (two brothers and father) against the mother - boys against girls. There's accusations from all sides, and you don't know who to believe. You have to race through the pages to decide for yourself. But the story is more than intriguing - the characters are filled with so much depth in the way they relate to each other.<br /><br />Right from the beginning, Eugene O'Neill had me intrigued with these characters. And as the character development went on, he swept me away in the pages.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13602306574234680742" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

